# Database design rules

Every schema change, migration, or data model must follow these rules. The AI must refuse to generate schema that violates them and explain why.

<!-- Ref: https://erflow.io/en/blog/database-schema-design-best-practices -->
<!-- Ref: https://playground.halfaccessible.com/blog/database-design-best-practices -->
<!-- Ref: https://bytebase.com/blog/top-database-schema-design-best-practices -->

## Naming conventions

- snake_case for all table names, column names, indexes, and constraints.
- Singular table names: `user`, `order`, `product` — not `users`, `orders`.
- Foreign keys: `<referenced_table>_id` (e.g. `user_id`, `category_id`).
- Boolean columns: prefix with `is_`, `has_`, or `can_` (e.g. `is_active`, `has_verified_email`).
- Timestamps: `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at` (soft delete).
- Indexes: `idx_<table>_<columns>` (e.g. `idx_order_user_id`).
- Constraints: `chk_<table>_<rule>`, `uq_<table>_<columns>`.

## Normalization

- Normalize to Third Normal Form (3NF) by default.
  - 1NF: Every column stores one atomic value. No arrays, no comma-separated lists in a column.
  - 2NF: Every non-key column depends on the entire primary key.
  - 3NF: No column depends on another non-key column.
- Only denormalize when you have measured a real performance problem AND documented the trade-off in an ADR.

## Primary keys

- Use auto-incrementing `BIGINT` (BIGSERIAL) for internal tables.
- Use UUIDs (v4 or v7) when IDs are exposed in URLs/APIs or the system is distributed.
- Never use natural keys (email, phone, SSN) as primary keys — they change.
- Every table gets a primary key. No exceptions.

## Foreign keys and integrity

- Always define `FOREIGN KEY` constraints in the database — not just in app code.
- Choose `ON DELETE` behavior explicitly:
  - `RESTRICT` (safe default — prevents orphans).
  - `CASCADE` only for true parent-child (e.g. delete order → delete order_items).
  - `SET NULL` only if the relationship is optional.
- Every relationship must have a foreign key constraint. If you skip it, explain why in a comment.

## Column defaults

- `NOT NULL` is the default stance. Only allow NULL when absence of a value is meaningful.
- Add `DEFAULT` values where sensible (e.g. `is_active DEFAULT true`, `created_at DEFAULT NOW()`).
- Use `DECIMAL` / `NUMERIC` for money — never FLOAT or DOUBLE.
- Use `TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE` for any time data. Store in UTC.
- Use the smallest data type that fits: SMALLINT for status codes, BOOLEAN for flags.

## Indexing

- Index every foreign key column.
- Index columns used in `WHERE`, `JOIN`, `ORDER BY`, and `GROUP BY`.
- Composite indexes: put the most selective column first.
- Do not blindly index every column — each index slows writes.
- If you add an index, add a comment explaining what query it serves.
- Review: `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` your critical queries before and after.

## Relationships

- One-to-Many: FK on the "many" side. Most common.
- Many-to-Many: junction/join table with composite PK or surrogate PK + unique constraint on the pair.
- One-to-One: FK with unique constraint, or merge into one table if both sides always exist.

## SQLite + Supabase (workspace default)

This workspace defaults to SQLite (local) syncing to Supabase (PostgreSQL, production). Follow these rules:

### SQLite (local/dev)
- Use `better-sqlite3` (synchronous, fast) or Drizzle ORM with SQLite adapter.
- SQLite has no `BIGSERIAL` — use `INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT` instead.
- SQLite has no native `TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE` — store ISO 8601 strings (`TEXT`) or Unix epoch (`INTEGER`). Use a consistent convention project-wide.
- SQLite has no `DECIMAL` type — store money as `INTEGER` in the smallest unit (cents/pence). E.g. $12.50 = `1250`.
- Enable `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL;` for concurrent reads.
- Enable `PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON;` — SQLite does NOT enforce foreign keys by default.

### Supabase (production/distributed)
- Supabase is PostgreSQL — all standard PostgreSQL rules in this file apply.
- Use Supabase migrations (`supabase db diff` / `supabase migration new`) or Drizzle push.
- Use Supabase Row Level Security (RLS) for access control — do not rely on app-level checks alone.
- Use Supabase realtime subscriptions for live data instead of polling.

### Sync strategy
- Write migrations in a shared schema definition (Drizzle recommended) that generates both SQLite and PostgreSQL.
- Local SQLite is the offline/fast cache. Supabase PostgreSQL is the source of truth.
- When a feature needs cloud sync: push local changes to Supabase, subscribe to remote changes.
- Document the sync boundary and conflict resolution strategy in an ADR.

## Migrations

- Every schema change goes through a migration file — never modify the DB by hand.
- Migrations must be reversible (include `up` and `down`).
- One logical change per migration (don't mix "add column" with "change index").
- Name migrations descriptively: `20260213_add_verified_at_to_user.sql`.
- For SQLite: use Drizzle `migrate()` or a custom runner. For Supabase: use `supabase migration new`.

## Soft delete

- Prefer soft delete (`deleted_at TIMESTAMP NULL`) for user-facing data.
- Add a partial index on `deleted_at IS NULL` to keep queries fast.
- Hard delete only for ephemeral data (logs, sessions, temp tokens).

## Common anti-patterns — reject these

| Anti-pattern | Why it's bad | Do this instead |
|---|---|---|
| Entity-Attribute-Value (EAV) | Kills query performance and integrity | Use JSONB column or proper relational tables |
| Storing comma-separated values | Violates 1NF, impossible to join/filter | Use a junction table |
| God table (one table for everything) | Unmanageable, violates SRP | Split by domain entity |
| No foreign keys ("the app handles it") | Data will become inconsistent | Always use DB-level constraints |
| `SELECT *` in application code | Fetches unnecessary data, breaks on schema changes | Explicitly list needed columns |
| N+1 queries via ORM | Fires one query per row instead of a join | Use eager loading / explicit joins |
| Storing money as FLOAT | Rounding errors lose real money | Use DECIMAL/NUMERIC |
| Nullable everything | Hides bugs, makes queries unpredictable | Default to NOT NULL |

## Checklist before merging any schema change

- [ ] All tables have a primary key
- [ ] All relationships have foreign key constraints
- [ ] ON DELETE behavior is explicitly chosen
- [ ] Naming follows snake_case conventions above
- [ ] Migration is reversible (has `down`)
- [ ] No 1NF violations (no arrays in columns, no CSV strings)
- [ ] Indexes exist for FKs and frequent query columns
- [ ] `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` run on critical queries
- [ ] No FLOAT/DOUBLE for money
- [ ] Timestamps use timezone-aware types and store UTC

## When NOT to enforce strictly

- Prototyping / spike with throwaway DB (but document that it's throwaway).
- Third-party schemas you don't control (adapt at the boundary).
- Time-series or analytics databases that intentionally denormalize for read performance (document in ADR).
